 inhabitants were not mentioned in the Biblical record. In Old Canaan in a New World, Elizabeth Fenton shows that though the Hebraic Indian theory may seem far-fetched today, it had a great deal of currency and significant influence over a very long period of American history. Indeed, at different times the idea that indigenous Americans were descended from the lost tribes of Israel was taken up to support political and religious positions on diverse issues including Christian millennialism, national expansion, trade policies, Jewish rights, sovereignty in the Americas, and scientific exploration. Through analysis of a wide collection of writings—from religious texts to novels—Fenton sheds light on a rarely explored but important part of religious discourse in early America. As the Hebraic Indian theory evolved over the course of two centuries, it revealed how religious belief and national interest intersected in early American history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aEthnologyzNorth America. 0aIndians of North AmericaxOrigin. 0aLost tribes of Israel. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  aA Son of the Forest.  aA Star in the West.  aAncestry.  aAppendix.  aBeyond the Verge.  aChristianity.  aDNA.  aDe Witt Clinton Chipman.  aElias Boudinot.  aEliza Snow.  aElizabeth Warren.  aEsdras.  aEthan Smith.  aHenry Home, Lord Kames.  aHollow earth.  aIews in America.  aJames Adair.  aJames Fenimore Cooper.  aJews in America.  aJohn Eliot.  aJoseph Smith, Jr.  aManual Mordecai Noah.  aMethodism.  aMormonism.  aMound builders.  aNative Americans.  aNorth America.  aRace.  aRacial science.  aRoger Williams.  aThe Bee-Hunter.  aThe Book of Mormon.  aThe History of the American Indians.  aThomas Thorowgood.  aUnited States.  aWilliam Apess.  aarchaeol